+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01STnFFzuhCYH8D416rZoiV3","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good, TypeScript compiles cleanly. Now let me conduct the thorough review.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Constraint-Based Event Scheduler\n\n### Overall Impression\n\nThe implementation is well-structured with clear separation of concerns (cycle detection, topological sort, greedy scheduling, batch optimization). All 31 tests pass and TypeScript compiles without errors. The code reads cleanly and the algorithm is sound for the described requirements.\n\nThat said, I have identified several issues ranging from critical correctness bugs to minor suggestions.\n\n---\n\n### CRITICAL Issues (Must Fix)\n\n#### 1. Prerequisite gap enforcement uses room gap instead of a dedicated prerequisite gap\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 176-187\n\nThe `earliestStart` function on line 183 uses the same `gap` variable for prerequisite timing as for room-to-room gaps:\n\n```typescript\nfunction earliestStart(eventId: string): number {\n    const event = eventMap.get(eventId)!;\n    let earliest = options.startTime;\n    if (event.prerequisites) {\n      for (const preId of event.prerequisites) {\n        const preAssign = assignments.find(a => a.eventId === preId);\n        if (!preAssign) return -1;\n        earliest = Math.max(earliest, preAssign.endTime + gap);\n      }\n    }\n    return earliest;\n  }\n```\n\nPer the spec, the prerequisite constraint is \"A must finish + gap before B starts.\" This is currently correct only if the spec intends the same gap for both room gaps and prerequisite gaps. The tests confirm this behavior (they check `a1.endTime + 15` for prerequisites), so this is consistent with the test suite. However, I want to flag that in a real conference scheduler, prerequisite gaps and room turnaround gaps often differ. **If the spec intends them to be the same value, this is fine. If not, this needs a separate `prerequisiteGap` option.**\n\n**Verdict:** Acceptable given the current spec, but worth noting for future extensibility.\n\n#### 2. Cycle detection silently ignores prerequisites referencing non-existent events\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 42-56\n\n```typescript\nfunction dfs(id: string): void {\n    color.set(id, GRAY);\n    const event = eventMap.get(id);\n    if (event?.prerequisites) {\n      for (const pre of event.prerequisites) {\n        if (pre === id || color.get(pre) === GRAY) {\n          throw new Error('Prerequisite cycle detected');\n        }\n        if (color.get(pre) === WHITE) {\n          dfs(pre);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n    color.set(id, BLACK);\n  }\n```\n\nIf a prerequisite ID refers to an event that does not exist in the input list, `color.get(pre)` returns `undefined`, which is neither `GRAY`, `WHITE`, nor `BLACK`. The DFS simply skips it. This is consistent across the codebase -- `topologicalSort` (line 76) also checks `ids.has(pre)` and `greedySchedule`'s `earliestStart` (line 181) will find no assignment and return `-1`, causing the event to be skipped.\n\n**This means an event with a prerequisite referencing a nonexistent event will be silently unschedulable.** The event will have `earliestStart` return `-1` and will be skipped in the greedy loop, but it will NOT appear in the `unscheduled` array because it is never explicitly added there -- wait, let me re-examine.\n\nActually, looking at line 256:\n```typescript\nconst unscheduled = [...eventMap.keys()].filter(id => !scheduled.has(id));\n```\n\nThe event WILL appear in `unscheduled` because it was never added to `scheduled`. So the behavior is correct -- it silently fails to schedule and reports the event as unscheduled. This is acceptable per the spec (\"Unscheduled events in unscheduled array, not throw\"). However, it would be more helpful to either (a) throw an error for referencing a non-existent prerequisite, or (b) treat the missing prerequisite as satisfied. The current behavior -- treating it as unsatisfied -- is the strictest interpretation but could be confusing to callers.\n\n**Verdict:** Not a bug per the spec, but a design concern worth documenting.\n\n---\n\n### IMPORTANT Issues (Should Fix)\n\n#### 3. `findSlot` has a subtle gap-before-first-event omission\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 189-199\n\n```typescript\nfunction findSlot(roomId: string, earliest: number, duration: number): number | null {\n    const slots = roomSlots.get(roomId)!;\n    let candidate = earliest;\n\n    for (const a of slots) {\n      if (candidate + duration <= a.startTime) break;\n      candidate = Math.max(candidate, a.endTime + gap);\n    }\n\n    return candidate + duration <= options.endTime ? candidate : null;\n  }\n```\n\nThis correctly finds the earliest available slot in a room. However, the gap is only enforced **after** existing events (`a.endTime + gap`), not **before** the first event. If `earliest` happens to be within the gap window preceding an existing event, the loop condition `candidate + duration <= a.startTime` would fail and then `candidate` would jump past that event. This is correct because the gap only needs to be enforced between consecutive events in the same room -- there is no requirement for a gap before the first event or after the last. So this logic is correct.\n\nHowever, there is an edge case: if `candidate` is set such that `candidate + duration` exactly equals `a.startTime` (no gap between the new event's end and the existing event's start), the `break` triggers and the event is placed at `candidate`. **This means there is no gap enforced BEFORE an existing event -- only AFTER.** Consider:\n\n- Room has event at [600, 660].\n- `candidate` = 540, `duration` = 60.\n- `candidate + duration` = 600 <= 600 (the existing event's startTime). The `break` fires.\n- New event is placed at [540, 600]. Existing event is at [600, 660]. Gap between them = 0.\n\n**This is a bug.** The gap should be enforced between any two events in the same room. The condition should be `candidate + duration + gap <= a.startTime`:\n\n```typescript\nif (candidate + duration + gap <= a.startTime) break;\n```\n\nWait -- let me think about this more carefully. The gap is a minimum gap between events in the same room. If event A ends at 600 and event B starts at 600, the gap is 0. With a default gap of 15, this should be disallowed.\n\nLet me re-read the existing logic more carefully. The loop iterates over existing slots sorted by start time. For the scenario above:\n- `candidate` = 540, `duration` = 60\n- First slot `a` has `startTime` = 600\n- `candidate + duration` = 600 <= 600 is `true`, so `break`\n- Event placed at [540, 600], existing event at [600, 660], gap = 0\n\n**This violates the gap constraint.** The fix should be:\n\n```typescript\nif (candidate + duration + gap <= a.startTime) break;\n```\n\n**However**, looking at the test results, all tests pass including gap tests. Let me examine why. In the test for \"respects default 15 minute gap\" (line 133), events are placed sequentially. The first event is placed in an empty room, so there is no collision. The second event enters `findSlot` with `earliest = 540` (or `options.startTime`). The loop finds the first event at `[540, 600]`. `candidate + duration = 540 + 60 = 600` which is NOT `<= 540` (the first event's start time), so we do NOT break. Instead, `candidate = max(540, 600 + 15) = 615`. Then `615 + 60 = 675 <= endTime`, so it returns 615. Gap is 615 - 600 = 15. Correct!\n\nThe problematic scenario would only occur when we try to place an event BEFORE an already-scheduled event in the same room. This can happen when a later-processed event has an earlier `earliest` time. Let me construct a concrete scenario:\n\n- Event A (duration 60, no prereqs) gets scheduled at [615, 675] (because the optimizer tried something that placed it later).\n- Event B (duration 60, no prereqs) then tries to schedule with `earliest = 540`.\n- `findSlot`: candidate=540, slot A at [615,675]. `540+60=600 <= 615` is true. Break. Place B at [540, 600].\n- Gap between B's end (600) and A's start (615) = 15. This is fine with gap=15.\n\nBut with a shorter gap or longer event:\n- Event A scheduled at [600, 660].\n- Event B (duration 60) tries with earliest=540.\n- `candidate + duration = 600 <= 600` is true. Break. Place B at [540, 600].\n- Gap = 0. **Bug confirmed.**\n\nThis specific scenario may not arise with the current orderings (since events are processed in topological/sorted order and typically placed at the earliest possible time), but it IS a latent bug that could surface with different orderings or input patterns.\n\n**Recommendation:** Change line 194 from:\n```typescript\nif (candidate + duration <= a.startTime) break;\n```\nto:\n```typescript\nif (candidate + duration + gap <= a.startTime) break;\n```\n\n#### 4. O(n) linear search for prerequisite assignments\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 181\n\n```typescript\nconst preAssign = assignments.find(a => a.eventId === preId);\n```\n\nThis is called inside `earliestStart`, which is called for every event in the ordering. For each event, it iterates over all prerequisites, and for each prerequisite, it does a linear scan of all assignments. In the worst case (chain of n events), this is O(n^2). For a conference scheduler with dozens or hundreds of events, this is fine. For larger scales, using a `Map<string, Assignment>` would be better.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add a `Map<string, Assignment>` for O(1) lookup:\n\n```typescript\nconst assignmentMap = new Map<string, Assignment>();\n// After placing an event:\nassignmentMap.set(eventId, a);\n// In earliestStart:\nconst preAssign = assignmentMap.get(preId);\n```\n\n#### 5. `topologicalSort` result may not include all events\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 63-101\n\nIf there are events whose prerequisites reference other events in the list that form a chain, but cycle detection already passed, the topological sort should include all events. However, the topological sort uses Kahn's algorithm, which only adds events with in-degree 0 to the queue. If a prerequisite references an event NOT in the input list, that prerequisite edge is ignored (line 76: `if (ids.has(pre))`), so the in-degree is correctly computed only for known events.\n\nThe result array from `topologicalSort` will only contain events that were reachable through the in-degree reduction process. If the cycle detection passed but some edge case caused an event to never reach in-degree 0, it would be silently omitted. After cycle detection, this should not happen for valid inputs. But there is no defensive check. The `ensureTopoValid` function (line 120) acts as a safety net by appending any remaining events.\n\n**Verdict:** Acceptable with the `ensureTopoValid` safety net, but worth adding a comment explaining why `ensureTopoValid` is necessary.\n\n#### 6. `ensureTopoValid` appends stuck events at the end without guarantees\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 157-158\n\n```typescript\n// Any truly stuck go at the end\nfor (const id of remaining) valid.push(id);\n```\n\nEvents that cannot be placed due to unmet prerequisites are appended at the end. In `greedySchedule`, these events will then have `earliestStart` return `-1` (because their prerequisite was not scheduled), so they will be skipped and end up in `unscheduled`. This is correct behavior.\n\n**Verdict:** Correct, but the comment could be more descriptive.\n\n---\n\n### SUGGESTIONS (Nice to Have)\n\n#### 7. The `makeSorted` function does not truly guarantee topological validity\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 278-285\n\n```typescript\nconst makeSorted = (comparator: (a: string, b: string) => number): string[] => {\n    return [...topoOrder].sort((a, b) => {\n      const da = getDepth(a, eventMap, depthCache);\n      const db = getDepth(b, eventMap, depthCache);\n      if (da !== db) return da - db;\n      return comparator(a, b);\n    });\n  };\n```\n\nThe depth-first tiebreaking attempts to maintain topological order by sorting by prerequisite depth. However, depth alone does not guarantee topological validity. Consider events A, B, C where B depends on A, and both A and C have depth 0. If the secondary comparator sorts C before A, and then B (depth 1) comes later, the ordering [C, A, B] is valid. But if A and B have the same depth (possible in a diamond dependency), the secondary sort could break topological order.\n\nThis is why `ensureTopoValid` exists -- it fixes any violations. But this means the \"optimization\" orderings may not actually produce different valid schedules if `ensureTopoValid` has to rearrange them significantly. The approach works but is somewhat inefficient.\n\n**Recommendation:** Consider using a modified Kahn's algorithm with a priority queue (sorted by the secondary criterion) to generate different valid topological orderings directly, rather than sorting and then fixing.\n\n#### 8. Room sorting is ascending by capacity, which favors small rooms\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 270\n\n```typescript\nconst sortedRooms = [...rooms].sort((a, b) => a.capacity - b.capacity);\n```\n\nEvents default to 1 attendee, so most events will be placed in the smallest available room. This is a reasonable \"best fit\" strategy that preserves large rooms for events that need them. This is good.\n\nHowever, in the fallback path (lines 239-245), the code iterates over `eligibleRooms` (which is filtered from `sortedRooms`) and picks the room with the earliest available slot (`bestSlot`). If two rooms have the same earliest slot, it picks the first one encountered, which is the smallest eligible room. This is good bin-packing behavior.\n\n**Verdict:** Good design choice.\n\n#### 9. No input validation\n\nThe function does not validate inputs beyond cycle detection. For example:\n- Negative durations\n- `startTime >= endTime`\n- Negative attendees\n- Duplicate event IDs\n- Duplicate room IDs\n\n**Recommendation:** Add basic input validation:\n\n```typescript\nif (options.startTime >= options.endTime) {\n  throw new Error('startTime must be less than endTime');\n}\nfor (const e of events) {\n  if (e.duration <= 0) throw new Error(`Event ${e.id} has non-positive duration`);\n}\n```\n\n#### 10. Missing test coverage for edge cases\n\nThe test suite is solid but missing some edge cases:\n- Event with prerequisite referencing a non-existent event ID\n- Duplicate event IDs in the input\n- Events with duration 0\n- `gap: 0` combined with prerequisites (should prerequisite gap also be 0?)\n- Very large number of events (performance test)\n- Preferred room that does not exist in the rooms list\n- Events where multiple orderings produce different results (to verify maximization)\n\n#### 11. Minor code quality observations\n\n- **Line 91**: `queue.shift()` is O(n) for arrays. For large event sets, consider using an actual queue data structure. For typical conference sizes (< 100 events), this is negligible.\n- **Lines 38**: The `WHITE/GRAY/BLACK` constants would be more readable as an enum or named constants outside the function.\n- **No JSDoc comments**: The exported `schedule` function and interfaces lack documentation. Adding JSDoc would improve the developer experience.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| # | Severity | Issue | Location |\n|---|----------|-------|----------|\n| 3 | **IMPORTANT** | Gap not enforced when placing event BEFORE existing event in same room | Line 194 |\n| 4 | **IMPORTANT** | O(n) linear scan for prerequisite assignments | Line 181 |\n| 9 | Suggestion | No input validation for negative durations, bad time windows, etc. | `schedule()` |\n| 7 | Suggestion | `makeSorted` does not guarantee topological validity directly | Lines 278-285 |\n| 10 | Suggestion | Missing test coverage for several edge cases | Test file |\n| 11 | Suggestion | Minor: `queue.shift()` O(n), no JSDoc, magic constants | Various |\n\n### What Was Done Well\n\n- Clean type definitions with well-named interfaces (`Event`, `Room`, `Assignment`, `ScheduleResult`)\n- Proper separation of concerns: cycle detection, topological sort, greedy scheduling, and batch optimization are all distinct functions\n- The multi-ordering batch optimization strategy is clever and effective for maximizing scheduled events\n- The `ensureTopoValid` safety net is a good defensive programming practice\n- The \"smallest eligible room\" strategy is good bin-packing behavior\n- Edge cases for empty inputs are handled cleanly (lines 261-262)\n- The test suite is comprehensive with good coverage of the core requirements\n- All constraints from the spec are addressed (capacity, time window, gaps, prerequisites, preferred rooms, cycle detection, unscheduled array)\n\n### Primary Recommendation\n\nThe most actionable fix is **Issue #3** -- the gap enforcement bug in `findSlot` at `/workspace/src/index.ts` line 194. While it may not trigger with current test inputs due to the typical scheduling order, it is a latent correctness bug that violates the room gap constraint when an event is placed in a time slot before an already-scheduled event in the same room. The fix is a one-line change from `candidate + duration <= a.startTime` to `candidate + duration + gap <= a.startTime`."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a519398 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 32521\ntool_uses: 10\nduration_ms: 115763</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"93a648c7-50d2-4ad9-a07e-73c9a4dc8bb0","uuid":"36a4ed21-bd88-4fda-ad8f-02e5d5bc68a5","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the implementation in src/index.ts for the constraint-based event scheduler. Look for:\n1. Correctness issues and edge cases\n2. Whether the scheduling algorithm properly maximizes the number of events scheduled\n3. Whether all the constraints from the spec are properly enforced (capacity, time window, gaps, prerequisites, preferred rooms, cycle detection)\n4. Code quality issues\n\nThe spec requirements are:\n- Room capacity: event attendees must not exceed room capacity\n- Time window: events must start/end within [startTime, endTime]\n- Room gaps: minimum gap between events in same room (default 15)\n- Prerequisites: if B requires A, A must finish + gap before B starts\n- Preferred room: honor if possible\n- Cycle detection: throw error on cycles including self-references\n- Batch optimization: maximize scheduled events count\n- Unscheduled events in unscheduled array (not throw)\n","agentId":"a519398","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good, TypeScript compiles cleanly. Now let me conduct the thorough review.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Constraint-Based Event Scheduler\n\n### Overall Impression\n\nThe implementation is well-structured with clear separation of concerns (cycle detection, topological sort, greedy scheduling, batch optimization). All 31 tests pass and TypeScript compiles without errors. The code reads cleanly and the algorithm is sound for the described requirements.\n\nThat said, I have identified several issues ranging from critical correctness bugs to minor suggestions.\n\n---\n\n### CRITICAL Issues (Must Fix)\n\n#### 1. Prerequisite gap enforcement uses room gap instead of a dedicated prerequisite gap\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 176-187\n\nThe `earliestStart` function on line 183 uses the same `gap` variable for prerequisite timing as for room-to-room gaps:\n\n```typescript\nfunction earliestStart(eventId: string): number {\n    const event = eventMap.get(eventId)!;\n    let earliest = options.startTime;\n    if (event.prerequisites) {\n      for (const preId of event.prerequisites) {\n        const preAssign = assignments.find(a => a.eventId === preId);\n        if (!preAssign) return -1;\n        earliest = Math.max(earliest, preAssign.endTime + gap);\n      }\n    }\n    return earliest;\n  }\n```\n\nPer the spec, the prerequisite constraint is \"A must finish + gap before B starts.\" This is currently correct only if the spec intends the same gap for both room gaps and prerequisite gaps. The tests confirm this behavior (they check `a1.endTime + 15` for prerequisites), so this is consistent with the test suite. However, I want to flag that in a real conference scheduler, prerequisite gaps and room turnaround gaps often differ. **If the spec intends them to be the same value, this is fine. If not, this needs a separate `prerequisiteGap` option.**\n\n**Verdict:** Acceptable given the current spec, but worth noting for future extensibility.\n\n#### 2. Cycle detection silently ignores prerequisites referencing non-existent events\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 42-56\n\n```typescript\nfunction dfs(id: string): void {\n    color.set(id, GRAY);\n    const event = eventMap.get(id);\n    if (event?.prerequisites) {\n      for (const pre of event.prerequisites) {\n        if (pre === id || color.get(pre) === GRAY) {\n          throw new Error('Prerequisite cycle detected');\n        }\n        if (color.get(pre) === WHITE) {\n          dfs(pre);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n    color.set(id, BLACK);\n  }\n```\n\nIf a prerequisite ID refers to an event that does not exist in the input list, `color.get(pre)` returns `undefined`, which is neither `GRAY`, `WHITE`, nor `BLACK`. The DFS simply skips it. This is consistent across the codebase -- `topologicalSort` (line 76) also checks `ids.has(pre)` and `greedySchedule`'s `earliestStart` (line 181) will find no assignment and return `-1`, causing the event to be skipped.\n\n**This means an event with a prerequisite referencing a nonexistent event will be silently unschedulable.** The event will have `earliestStart` return `-1` and will be skipped in the greedy loop, but it will NOT appear in the `unscheduled` array because it is never explicitly added there -- wait, let me re-examine.\n\nActually, looking at line 256:\n```typescript\nconst unscheduled = [...eventMap.keys()].filter(id => !scheduled.has(id));\n```\n\nThe event WILL appear in `unscheduled` because it was never added to `scheduled`. So the behavior is correct -- it silently fails to schedule and reports the event as unscheduled. This is acceptable per the spec (\"Unscheduled events in unscheduled array, not throw\"). However, it would be more helpful to either (a) throw an error for referencing a non-existent prerequisite, or (b) treat the missing prerequisite as satisfied. The current behavior -- treating it as unsatisfied -- is the strictest interpretation but could be confusing to callers.\n\n**Verdict:** Not a bug per the spec, but a design concern worth documenting.\n\n---\n\n### IMPORTANT Issues (Should Fix)\n\n#### 3. `findSlot` has a subtle gap-before-first-event omission\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 189-199\n\n```typescript\nfunction findSlot(roomId: string, earliest: number, duration: number): number | null {\n    const slots = roomSlots.get(roomId)!;\n    let candidate = earliest;\n\n    for (const a of slots) {\n      if (candidate + duration <= a.startTime) break;\n      candidate = Math.max(candidate, a.endTime + gap);\n    }\n\n    return candidate + duration <= options.endTime ? candidate : null;\n  }\n```\n\nThis correctly finds the earliest available slot in a room. However, the gap is only enforced **after** existing events (`a.endTime + gap`), not **before** the first event. If `earliest` happens to be within the gap window preceding an existing event, the loop condition `candidate + duration <= a.startTime` would fail and then `candidate` would jump past that event. This is correct because the gap only needs to be enforced between consecutive events in the same room -- there is no requirement for a gap before the first event or after the last. So this logic is correct.\n\nHowever, there is an edge case: if `candidate` is set such that `candidate + duration` exactly equals `a.startTime` (no gap between the new event's end and the existing event's start), the `break` triggers and the event is placed at `candidate`. **This means there is no gap enforced BEFORE an existing event -- only AFTER.** Consider:\n\n- Room has event at [600, 660].\n- `candidate` = 540, `duration` = 60.\n- `candidate + duration` = 600 <= 600 (the existing event's startTime). The `break` fires.\n- New event is placed at [540, 600]. Existing event is at [600, 660]. Gap between them = 0.\n\n**This is a bug.** The gap should be enforced between any two events in the same room. The condition should be `candidate + duration + gap <= a.startTime`:\n\n```typescript\nif (candidate + duration + gap <= a.startTime) break;\n```\n\nWait -- let me think about this more carefully. The gap is a minimum gap between events in the same room. If event A ends at 600 and event B starts at 600, the gap is 0. With a default gap of 15, this should be disallowed.\n\nLet me re-read the existing logic more carefully. The loop iterates over existing slots sorted by start time. For the scenario above:\n- `candidate` = 540, `duration` = 60\n- First slot `a` has `startTime` = 600\n- `candidate + duration` = 600 <= 600 is `true`, so `break`\n- Event placed at [540, 600], existing event at [600, 660], gap = 0\n\n**This violates the gap constraint.** The fix should be:\n\n```typescript\nif (candidate + duration + gap <= a.startTime) break;\n```\n\n**However**, looking at the test results, all tests pass including gap tests. Let me examine why. In the test for \"respects default 15 minute gap\" (line 133), events are placed sequentially. The first event is placed in an empty room, so there is no collision. The second event enters `findSlot` with `earliest = 540` (or `options.startTime`). The loop finds the first event at `[540, 600]`. `candidate + duration = 540 + 60 = 600` which is NOT `<= 540` (the first event's start time), so we do NOT break. Instead, `candidate = max(540, 600 + 15) = 615`. Then `615 + 60 = 675 <= endTime`, so it returns 615. Gap is 615 - 600 = 15. Correct!\n\nThe problematic scenario would only occur when we try to place an event BEFORE an already-scheduled event in the same room. This can happen when a later-processed event has an earlier `earliest` time. Let me construct a concrete scenario:\n\n- Event A (duration 60, no prereqs) gets scheduled at [615, 675] (because the optimizer tried something that placed it later).\n- Event B (duration 60, no prereqs) then tries to schedule with `earliest = 540`.\n- `findSlot`: candidate=540, slot A at [615,675]. `540+60=600 <= 615` is true. Break. Place B at [540, 600].\n- Gap between B's end (600) and A's start (615) = 15. This is fine with gap=15.\n\nBut with a shorter gap or longer event:\n- Event A scheduled at [600, 660].\n- Event B (duration 60) tries with earliest=540.\n- `candidate + duration = 600 <= 600` is true. Break. Place B at [540, 600].\n- Gap = 0. **Bug confirmed.**\n\nThis specific scenario may not arise with the current orderings (since events are processed in topological/sorted order and typically placed at the earliest possible time), but it IS a latent bug that could surface with different orderings or input patterns.\n\n**Recommendation:** Change line 194 from:\n```typescript\nif (candidate + duration <= a.startTime) break;\n```\nto:\n```typescript\nif (candidate + duration + gap <= a.startTime) break;\n```\n\n#### 4. O(n) linear search for prerequisite assignments\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 181\n\n```typescript\nconst preAssign = assignments.find(a => a.eventId === preId);\n```\n\nThis is called inside `earliestStart`, which is called for every event in the ordering. For each event, it iterates over all prerequisites, and for each prerequisite, it does a linear scan of all assignments. In the worst case (chain of n events), this is O(n^2). For a conference scheduler with dozens or hundreds of events, this is fine. For larger scales, using a `Map<string, Assignment>` would be better.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add a `Map<string, Assignment>` for O(1) lookup:\n\n```typescript\nconst assignmentMap = new Map<string, Assignment>();\n// After placing an event:\nassignmentMap.set(eventId, a);\n// In earliestStart:\nconst preAssign = assignmentMap.get(preId);\n```\n\n#### 5. `topologicalSort` result may not include all events\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 63-101\n\nIf there are events whose prerequisites reference other events in the list that form a chain, but cycle detection already passed, the topological sort should include all events. However, the topological sort uses Kahn's algorithm, which only adds events with in-degree 0 to the queue. If a prerequisite references an event NOT in the input list, that prerequisite edge is ignored (line 76: `if (ids.has(pre))`), so the in-degree is correctly computed only for known events.\n\nThe result array from `topologicalSort` will only contain events that were reachable through the in-degree reduction process. If the cycle detection passed but some edge case caused an event to never reach in-degree 0, it would be silently omitted. After cycle detection, this should not happen for valid inputs. But there is no defensive check. The `ensureTopoValid` function (line 120) acts as a safety net by appending any remaining events.\n\n**Verdict:** Acceptable with the `ensureTopoValid` safety net, but worth adding a comment explaining why `ensureTopoValid` is necessary.\n\n#### 6. `ensureTopoValid` appends stuck events at the end without guarantees\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 157-158\n\n```typescript\n// Any truly stuck go at the end\nfor (const id of remaining) valid.push(id);\n```\n\nEvents that cannot be placed due to unmet prerequisites are appended at the end. In `greedySchedule`, these events will then have `earliestStart` return `-1` (because their prerequisite was not scheduled), so they will be skipped and end up in `unscheduled`. This is correct behavior.\n\n**Verdict:** Correct, but the comment could be more descriptive.\n\n---\n\n### SUGGESTIONS (Nice to Have)\n\n#### 7. The `makeSorted` function does not truly guarantee topological validity\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 278-285\n\n```typescript\nconst makeSorted = (comparator: (a: string, b: string) => number): string[] => {\n    return [...topoOrder].sort((a, b) => {\n      const da = getDepth(a, eventMap, depthCache);\n      const db = getDepth(b, eventMap, depthCache);\n      if (da !== db) return da - db;\n      return comparator(a, b);\n    });\n  };\n```\n\nThe depth-first tiebreaking attempts to maintain topological order by sorting by prerequisite depth. However, depth alone does not guarantee topological validity. Consider events A, B, C where B depends on A, and both A and C have depth 0. If the secondary comparator sorts C before A, and then B (depth 1) comes later, the ordering [C, A, B] is valid. But if A and B have the same depth (possible in a diamond dependency), the secondary sort could break topological order.\n\nThis is why `ensureTopoValid` exists -- it fixes any violations. But this means the \"optimization\" orderings may not actually produce different valid schedules if `ensureTopoValid` has to rearrange them significantly. The approach works but is somewhat inefficient.\n\n**Recommendation:** Consider using a modified Kahn's algorithm with a priority queue (sorted by the secondary criterion) to generate different valid topological orderings directly, rather than sorting and then fixing.\n\n#### 8. Room sorting is ascending by capacity, which favors small rooms\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 270\n\n```typescript\nconst sortedRooms = [...rooms].sort((a, b) => a.capacity - b.capacity);\n```\n\nEvents default to 1 attendee, so most events will be placed in the smallest available room. This is a reasonable \"best fit\" strategy that preserves large rooms for events that need them. This is good.\n\nHowever, in the fallback path (lines 239-245), the code iterates over `eligibleRooms` (which is filtered from `sortedRooms`) and picks the room with the earliest available slot (`bestSlot`). If two rooms have the same earliest slot, it picks the first one encountered, which is the smallest eligible room. This is good bin-packing behavior.\n\n**Verdict:** Good design choice.\n\n#### 9. No input validation\n\nThe function does not validate inputs beyond cycle detection. For example:\n- Negative durations\n- `startTime >= endTime`\n- Negative attendees\n- Duplicate event IDs\n- Duplicate room IDs\n\n**Recommendation:** Add basic input validation:\n\n```typescript\nif (options.startTime >= options.endTime) {\n  throw new Error('startTime must be less than endTime');\n}\nfor (const e of events) {\n  if (e.duration <= 0) throw new Error(`Event ${e.id} has non-positive duration`);\n}\n```\n\n#### 10. Missing test coverage for edge cases\n\nThe test suite is solid but missing some edge cases:\n- Event with prerequisite referencing a non-existent event ID\n- Duplicate event IDs in the input\n- Events with duration 0\n- `gap: 0` combined with prerequisites (should prerequisite gap also be 0?)\n- Very large number of events (performance test)\n- Preferred room that does not exist in the rooms list\n- Events where multiple orderings produce different results (to verify maximization)\n\n#### 11. Minor code quality observations\n\n- **Line 91**: `queue.shift()` is O(n) for arrays. For large event sets, consider using an actual queue data structure. For typical conference sizes (< 100 events), this is negligible.\n- **Lines 38**: The `WHITE/GRAY/BLACK` constants would be more readable as an enum or named constants outside the function.\n- **No JSDoc comments**: The exported `schedule` function and interfaces lack documentation. Adding JSDoc would improve the developer experience.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| # | Severity | Issue | Location |\n|---|----------|-------|----------|\n| 3 | **IMPORTANT** | Gap not enforced when placing event BEFORE existing event in same room | Line 194 |\n| 4 | **IMPORTANT** | O(n) linear scan for prerequisite assignments | Line 181 |\n| 9 | Suggestion | No input validation for negative durations, bad time windows, etc. | `schedule()` |\n| 7 | Suggestion | `makeSorted` does not guarantee topological validity directly | Lines 278-285 |\n| 10 | Suggestion | Missing test coverage for several edge cases | Test file |\n| 11 | Suggestion | Minor: `queue.shift()` O(n), no JSDoc, magic constants | Various |\n\n### What Was Done Well\n\n- Clean type definitions with well-named interfaces (`Event`, `Room`, `Assignment`, `ScheduleResult`)\n- Proper separation of concerns: cycle detection, topological sort, greedy scheduling, and batch optimization are all distinct functions\n- The multi-ordering batch optimization strategy is clever and effective for maximizing scheduled events\n- The `ensureTopoValid` safety net is a good defensive programming practice\n- The \"smallest eligible room\" strategy is good bin-packing behavior\n- Edge cases for empty inputs are handled cleanly (lines 261-262)\n- The test suite is comprehensive with good coverage of the core requirements\n- All constraints from the spec are addressed (capacity, time window, gaps, prerequisites, preferred rooms, cycle detection, unscheduled array)\n\n### Primary Recommendation\n\nThe most actionable fix is **Issue #3** -- the gap enforcement bug in `findSlot` at `/workspace/src/index.ts` line 194. While it may not trigger with current test inputs due to the typical scheduling order, it is a latent correctness bug that violates the room gap constraint when an event is placed in a time slot before an already-scheduled event in the same room. The fix is a one-line change from `candidate + duration <= a.startTime` to `candidate + duration + gap <= a.startTime`."}],"totalDurationMs":115763,"totalTokens":32521,"totalToolUseCount":10,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input